  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash originates in SLPVectorizerPass::vectorizeCmpInsts during the sorting/comparison of compare instructions
(compareCmp). The assertion in dyn_cast(Value*) indicates we attempted to dyn_cast an operand Value* that is no longer a valid, present IR value (i.e., it has been
deleted/invalidated). This typically happens when the pass deletes or replaces instructions while still keeping stale references in collections it processes
later.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows SLP schedules, vectorizes, and then erases a large chain of scalars, including:\n- scalar ops feeding
%i22\n- PHIs (%i and %i2)\n- the selects (%i24, %i26)\n- finally the compares themselves (%i23, %i25)\n\nThe sequence within vectorizeCmpInsts is:\n- First loop:
try vectorizeRootInstruction for operands of compares.\n- Second loop: tryToVectorize each compare.\n- Third stage: collect compares into Vals and sort with
CompareSorter and AreCompatibleCompares, then tryToVectorizeSequence.\n\nThe log shows that erasure of many nodes happens during vectorization before the final
stage. Importantly, the erasure includes the compare instructions and their operands. The subsequent sorting in vectorizeCmpInsts accesses compare operands via
getOperand and dyn_cast<Instruction>(Op1) in compareCmp. If an operand has been deleted (e.g., as part of the earlier transformations), the compare may temporarily
still exist (or a WeakTrackingVH in the pipeline might resolve to a tombstone), leading to dyn_cast encountering a non-existent value and asserting.\n\n3. Root
Cause Analysis:\n- vectorizeCmpInsts builds Vals from the original CmpInsts without checking whether their operands are still valid.\n- While it does filter out
deleted compares via R.isDeleted(V), it does not filter compares whose operands are deleted instructions. This violates the expectation in compareCmp that operands
are valid Values.\n- After earlier transformations and erasures, some compares may still be non-deleted (from R's perspective) while their operand(s) are
instructions that have been deleted, causing compareCmp's dyn_cast<Instruction>(Op1) to hit an invalid/non-present Value and assert.\n\nThus, the first
transformation point leads to deletions that invalidate operands, and the subsequent collection/sorting step fails to account for that, causing the crash.\n\n4.
Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe should make vectorizeCmpInsts robust to deleted operands by filtering out compares whose operands are deleted instructions. Add a check
when populating Vals to ensure that for each compare, any Instruction operands are not marked deleted by R. If any operand is a deleted Instruction, skip this
compare from Vals.\n\nEdit at lines 21174-21178 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp:\nReplace the current Vals push logic with an extended
filter:\n\nCurrent:\n  SmallVector<Value *> Vals;\n  for (Instruction *V : CmpInsts)\n    if (!R.isDeleted(V) && isValidElementType(getValueType(V)))\n
Vals.push_back(V);\n\nProposed:\n  SmallVector<Value *> Vals;\n  for (Instruction *V : CmpInsts) {\n    if (R.isDeleted(V) ||
!isValidElementType(getValueType(V)))\n      continue;\n    // Ensure operands are still present and not deleted instructions.\n    bool OperandsAreValid = true;\n
for (Value *Op : V->operands()) {\n      if (auto *OpI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Op)) {\n        if (R.isDeleted(OpI)) {\n          OperandsAreValid = false;\n
break;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n    if (!OperandsAreValid)\n      continue;\n    Vals.push_back(V);\n  }\n\nThis ensures we don't sort or compare compares whose
operands are deleted, avoiding use of invalid Values in compareCmp.\n\nNOTICE: Since the assertion indicates a non-existent Value during dyn_cast, we assume
assertions are correct and prevent earlier invalid state by skipping compares with invalid/deleted operands.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy filtering out compares with
deleted instruction operands before sorting and vectorizing the list, we prevent compareCmp from seeing invalid operands and triggering the dyn_cast assertion.
This preserves correctness in the presence of earlier transformations that erase parts of the compare chains, and is consistent with the pass's existing practice
